Notes of java
----------------------

JDK
(Java Development Kit)
The JDK also called Java Development Kit is a superset of the JRE, and contains everything that is in the JRE, plus tools such as the compilers and debuggers
necessary for developina applets and applications.


JRE
(Java Runtime Environment)
JRE : The Java Runtime Environment (JRE) provides the libraries, the Java Virtual Machine, and other components to run applets and applications written in the
Java programming language. JRE does not contain tools and utilities such as compilers or debuggers for developing applets and applications.


JVM
(Java Virtual Machine)
Java virtual Machine(JVM) is a virtual Machine that provides runtime environment to execute java byte code. The JVM doesn't understand Java
code directly, that's why you need to compile your java files to obtain *. class files that contain the bytecodes understandable by the JVM.

java => compile => .class (Bytecodes)
java is also called 2 stage system
1) javaprogram	> compiler > byte codes
2) Byte code > interpreter > execute




Here's a simple diagram showing the relationship:
. JDK (Java Development Kit) - Contains everything (for development).
. Inside it is JRE (Java Runtime Environment) - Used to run Java apps.
. Inside JRE is JVM (Java Virtual Machine) - Actually executes the code.

----------------------------------------------

Increment Decrement Operator in Java
------------------------------------------
Increment operator(++) or Decrement operator(--) used to increase the  value of the variable by one or decrease the value of the variable by one
respectively.
For Example: 1.
int a=5;
a++; // The value of a will become 6

2.int b=10;
a -- ;// The value of b will become 9

a++ = [a=a+1]
b-- = [b=b-1]


Increment / Decrement Operator
Further, increment/decrement operator is classified into two parts:
a. Prefix Increment/Decrement  = ++a, --a
b. Postfix Increment/Decrement  = a++, a--


Prefix Increment / Decrement Operator
When ++ or -- is placed before the variable, it is called a prefix operator.
In this case, the variable’s value is changed first, and then the updated value is used in the expression.
int a = 5;
System.out.println(++a); // 6 (first increment, then use)
System.out.println(a);   // 6


Posftfix Increment / Decrement Operator
When ++ or -- is placed after the variable, it is called a postfix operator.
In this case, the current value is used first, and then the variable is updated.
int a = 5;
System.out.println(a++); // 5 (first use, then increment)
System.out.println(a);   // 6

So the difference is:
---------------------------------
Prefix: Change first → then use.
Postfix: Use first → then change.



AND OR NOT Logical Operators In Java 
----------------------------------------------
There may be some requirements where two or more conditions have to be joined together. In such places, Logical operators are used to combine multiple
conditions.
There are three Logical Operators are:
1. AND Operator - &&
This returns true when all the conditions associated with this is true. In simple words we may say that this finally gives true when every condition is satisfied.


2. OR Operator - ||
This returns true when any one condition associated with this is true. In simple words we may say that this finally gives true when any one condition is
satisfied.


3. Not Operator - !
This reverses the condition. Basically it is used to reverse the input. i.e. if the input is true it returns faise and if the input is false it returns true.


\n :- used in java prommiging to change the line while printing.
ex. syso("value of a : " + a +"value of b :" + b);
console result :-
value of a :5 value of b : 10
 if we want to seperately print the message in next line then
 syso("value of a : " + a +"\nvalue of b :" + b);
console result :-
value of a :5 
value of b : 10














































